amdgpu: uvd_v4_2 — Sony-style per-vmid 2-level PD (v76e-B1)

Mainline 5.x amdgpu shares a single flat GART across VMIDs 1..15 (VC1_CNTL
DEPTH=1 + the same PT_BASE = gart.bo). Sony's gbase_create_vmid
(FUN_c8867260, decompiled this iteration) does the opposite: every
non-system VMID gets its own physically-contiguous PD (entries × 8 bytes,
allocated via kmem_alloc_contig). Each PD entry covers 8 MB
(block_size = 11, not mainline's default 9), each PT page is 16 KB
holding 2048 entries × 8 bytes. Sony's VM_CONTEXT1_CNTL value
(0x32fffeda) confirms PAGE_TABLE_BLOCK_SIZE field = 2.

For our 3.1 MB region 1+2+3 at 0x300000000:
  PD index = 0x300000000 >> 23 = 0x600
  One 16 KB PT page covers VAs 0x300000000..0x300800000 — well past 3.1 MB.

This patch adds uvd_v4_2_setup_vmid_pd_liverpool() that:
  1. Allocates a 32 KB PD BO and a 16 KB PT BO, both in VRAM (must be
     physically contiguous — GMC walks raw memory, not GART).
  2. Populates the PT with mirror BO's per-page DMA addresses (PTE flags
     match mainline: VALID | SYSTEM | READABLE | WRITEABLE).
  3. Populates PD[0x600] with the PT's physical address + VALID bit
     (matching Sony's gbase_write_pte: pt_phys | 1).
  4. Repoints VC1..VC15 PT_BASE_ADDR registers at the new PD.
  5. Restores VM_CONTEXT1_CNTL.PAGE_TABLE_DEPTH = 1 (undoing β-2-A's
     DEPTH=0 override) and sets PAGE_TABLE_BLOCK_SIZE = 2.
  6. Issues a VM_INVALIDATE_REQUEST = 0xfffe (VC1..VC15).

Why ALL VC1..VC15, not just VC4? VC1_CNTL governs VC1..VC15 jointly on
CIK GMC, so DEPTH must change for the whole group. We point every
non-system VMID at the same minimal PD (only entry 0x600 is valid). Any
non-UVD walk faults — but those aren't happening pre-userspace.

Calls into start_liverpool right after setup_fw_mirror_liverpool so the
mirror BO's dma_address array is populated before we read from it.

Existing A-arc patches deliberately kept:
  - Mirror BO + Sony IOCTL constants (A2/A15) — still written; fw reads them
  - mirror gart_bind at 0x300000000 (A2/A4) — leaves stale entries in
    the FLAT GART that VC1+ no longer walks; harmless
  - Dummy bind at GART VA 0 (A1.5) — harmless
  - VC1 CNTL DEPTH=0 override (β-2-A in gmc_v7_0.c) — UNDONE here

Why this might work where A-arc didn't:
  - A-arc forced flat walk (DEPTH=0); GMC reads PTE directly at
    gart.ptr[VA>>12]. UVD's read of 0x300000000 succeeded but the
    fw never asserted STATUS bit 1.
  - Hypothesis: the fw's bring-up routine internally walks more than
    just the literal VA 0x300000000 — it may issue DMAs across the
    full 8 MB block, or rely on FRAG bits / PDE flags in the entries
    it sees.
  - B1 gives it a real, Sony-shaped 2-level walk. Same physical pages
    end up in the PTEs, but the structural shape now matches the fw's
    expectation.

Expected hardware signals:

  ✅ STATUS bit 1 sets — Sony's PD structure was the missing piece.
     Narrow down whether it's DEPTH/BLOCK_SIZE/PD-shape that mattered.

  🟡 Cache sample pattern changes meaningfully (not just k-divider
     periodicity) — fw saw something different through the new walk.
     Useful information either way.

  ❌ Identical sample table (STATUS=0x4 forever) — Sony's PD shape
     isn't the gate. Pivot to deep Ghidra dig of Orbis-side pre-UVD init
     (what Orbis touches BEFORE userspace opens UVD).

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
@@ -41,6 +41,10 @@
 #include "smu/smu_7_0_1_d.h"
 #include "smu/smu_7_0_1_sh_mask.h"
 
+/* v76e-B1: VM_CONTEXT* / VM_INVALIDATE_REQUEST register offsets + CNTL fields */
+#include "gmc/gmc_7_1_d.h"
+#include "gmc/gmc_7_1_sh_mask.h"
+
 static void uvd_v4_2_mc_resume(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
 static void uvd_v4_2_set_ring_funcs(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
 static void uvd_v4_2_set_irq_funcs(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
@@ -476,8 +480,52 @@
 				 PS4_UVD_REGION3_SIZE)	/* 3.1 MB */
 #define PS4_UVD_FW_MIRROR_VA	0x300000000ULL		/* Sony's region 1 VA */
 
+/*
+ * v76e-B1: per-vmid 2-level page directory mimicking Sony's gbase_create_vmid
+ * (FUN_c8867260) + gbase_write_pte (FUN_c88661c0).
+ *
+ * Sony's layout (decoded from Ghidra):
+ *   - VM_CONTEXT1_CNTL.PAGE_TABLE_BLOCK_SIZE = 2  (Sony's CNTL = 0x32fffeda,
+ *     field at bits 24-27 = 2 → block_size_log2 = 11)
+ *   - Each PD entry covers 8 MB of VA (va_size >> 0x17 entries per PD)
+ *   - Each PT page is 16 KB (2048 entries × 8 bytes), covers 8 MB
+ *   - PTE format: phys & ~0xFFF | (flags & 0xFFF)
+ *   - PDE format: pt_phys & ~0xFFF | 1  (VALID only)
+ *
+ * Mainline default is block_size = 9 (PD entry = 2 MB, PT page = 4 KB / 512
+ * entries). For a 3.1 MB region, Sony's layout uses ONE 16 KB PT page; the
+ * mainline layout would need two 4 KB PT pages. We follow Sony — simpler.
+ *
+ * For a 32 GB VC range with block_size = 11:
+ *   PD entries = 32 GB / 8 MB = 4096 → PD size = 32 KB
+ *   VA 0x300000000 → PD index = 0x300000000 >> 23 = 0x600
+ *   PT page 0 (16 KB) covers 0x300000000..0x300800000, well past our 3.1 MB.
+ *
+ * We allocate PD/PT in VRAM (must be physically contiguous — GMC walks raw
+ * memory, not through GART). Both PD and PT entries point at our fw mirror
+ * BO's per-page DMA addresses (mirror is GTT-domain).
+ *
+ * Existing A patches we deliberately keep:
+ *   - Mirror BO + Sony IOCTL constants (A2/A15) — still written, fw reads them
+ *   - mirror gart_bind at 0x300000000 (A2/A4) — leaves stale entries in
+ *     the FLAT GART that VC1+ no longer walks; harmless
+ *   - Dummy bind at GART VA 0 (A1.5) — harmless
+ *   - VC1 CNTL DEPTH=0 override (β-2-A) — REVERTED here back to DEPTH=1 +
+ *     BLOCK_SIZE=2
+ */
+#define PS4_UVD_PD_BLOCK_BITS	23		/* Sony: 8 MB per PD entry */
+#define PS4_UVD_PT_ENTRIES	2048		/* 16 KB PT page */
+#define PS4_UVD_PT_SIZE		(PS4_UVD_PT_ENTRIES * 8)
+#define PS4_UVD_PD_ENTRIES	((32ULL << 30) >> PS4_UVD_PD_BLOCK_BITS)
+#define PS4_UVD_PD_SIZE		(PS4_UVD_PD_ENTRIES * 8)
+#define PS4_UVD_PD_INDEX	(PS4_UVD_FW_MIRROR_VA >> PS4_UVD_PD_BLOCK_BITS)
+#define PS4_UVD_CNTL_BLOCK_SIZE	2
+
 static struct amdgpu_bo *uvd_fw_mirror_bo;
 static bool uvd_fw_mirror_done;
+static struct amdgpu_bo *uvd_vmid_pd_bo;
+static struct amdgpu_bo *uvd_vmid_pt_bo;
+static bool uvd_vmid_pd_done;
 
 static int uvd_v4_2_setup_fw_mirror_liverpool(struct amdgpu_device *adev)
 {
@@ -577,6 +625,120 @@
 	return 0;
 }
 
+/*
+ * v76e-B1: build a Sony-style 2-level page directory for the UVD VMID, then
+ * re-point ALL VC1..VC15 PT_BASE registers at that PD and update VC1_CNTL
+ * for DEPTH=1 + BLOCK_SIZE=2.
+ *
+ * Why all VC1..VC15 (not just VC4)? VC1_CNTL governs VC1..VC15 jointly on CIK
+ * GMC. Switching the cntl to DEPTH=1 means every non-system VMID must have a
+ * valid PD; mainline's flat GART value in PT_BASE would be interpreted as a
+ * PD and walked into garbage. Cleanest fix: point every non-system VMID at
+ * the same minimal PD. The PD only has the single 0x600 entry mapped (region
+ * 1+2+3), so any walk other than the UVD region faults — but those other
+ * walks aren't happening pre-userspace.
+ *
+ * Compare to v76d-β-2-A which forced DEPTH=0 (flat) for all VC1+. That
+ * worked for UVD's read-at-0x300000000 path but diverges from Sony's hardware
+ * model and may starve the fw of something it expects to see in a real PD
+ * walk (e.g., FRAG bits, multi-page contiguous hint, etc.).
+ */
+static int uvd_v4_2_setup_vmid_pd_liverpool(struct amdgpu_device *adev)
+{
+	u64 pd_gpu_addr, pt_gpu_addr;
+	void *pd_cpu_addr_v, *pt_cpu_addr_v;
+	u64 __iomem *pd_iomem;
+	u64 __iomem *pt_iomem;
+	struct ttm_tt *mirror_ttm;
+	int r, i, mirror_pages;
+	u32 tmp;
+	const u64 pte_flags = AMDGPU_PTE_VALID | AMDGPU_PTE_SYSTEM |
+			      AMDGPU_PTE_READABLE | AMDGPU_PTE_WRITEABLE;
+	const u64 pde_flags = AMDGPU_PTE_VALID;	/* Sony writes pt_phys | 1 */
+
+	if (uvd_vmid_pd_done)
+		return 0;
+
+	if (!uvd_fw_mirror_bo) {
+		DRM_ERROR("ps4 uvd: B1 mirror BO missing — fw_mirror_setup must run first\n");
+		return -EINVAL;
+	}
+	mirror_ttm = uvd_fw_mirror_bo->tbo.ttm;
+	if (!mirror_ttm || !mirror_ttm->dma_address) {
+		DRM_ERROR("ps4 uvd: B1 mirror BO has no dma_address\n");
+		return -EINVAL;
+	}
+
+	/*
+	 * Allocate PD (32 KB) and PT (16 KB) in VRAM — must be physically
+	 * contiguous so GMC's PT walker can stride through them.
+	 */
+	r = amdgpu_bo_create_kernel(adev, PS4_UVD_PD_SIZE, PAGE_SIZE,
+				    AMDGPU_GEM_DOMAIN_VRAM,
+				    &uvd_vmid_pd_bo, &pd_gpu_addr, &pd_cpu_addr_v);
+	if (r) {
+		DRM_ERROR("ps4 uvd: B1 PD alloc failed: %d\n", r);
+		return r;
+	}
+	r = amdgpu_bo_create_kernel(adev, PS4_UVD_PT_SIZE, PAGE_SIZE,
+				    AMDGPU_GEM_DOMAIN_VRAM,
+				    &uvd_vmid_pt_bo, &pt_gpu_addr, &pt_cpu_addr_v);
+	if (r) {
+		DRM_ERROR("ps4 uvd: B1 PT alloc failed: %d\n", r);
+		amdgpu_bo_free_kernel(&uvd_vmid_pd_bo, NULL, NULL);
+		return r;
+	}
+
+	pd_iomem = (u64 __iomem *)pd_cpu_addr_v;
+	pt_iomem = (u64 __iomem *)pt_cpu_addr_v;
+	memset_io(pd_iomem, 0, PS4_UVD_PD_SIZE);
+	memset_io(pt_iomem, 0, PS4_UVD_PT_SIZE);
+
+	/* Populate PT with mirror BO pages 0..(PS4_UVD_REGIONS_TOTAL / PAGE_SIZE - 1). */
+	mirror_pages = PS4_UVD_REGIONS_TOTAL / PAGE_SIZE;
+	for (i = 0; i < mirror_pages; i++) {
+		u64 page_pa = mirror_ttm->dma_address[i];
+		u64 pte = (page_pa & ~(u64)0xFFFULL) | pte_flags;
+		writeq(pte, &pt_iomem[i]);
+	}
+
+	/* Populate the single PD entry pointing at our PT. */
+	writeq((pt_gpu_addr & ~(u64)0xFFFULL) | pde_flags,
+	       &pd_iomem[PS4_UVD_PD_INDEX]);
+
+	/*
+	 * Repoint VC1..VC15 PT_BASE at the new PD. Sony writes the PD's
+	 * physical address >> 12 to the per-vmid PT_BASE register.
+	 */
+	for (i = 1; i <= 7; i++)
+		WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT0_PAGE_TABLE_BASE_ADDR + i,
+		       pd_gpu_addr >> 12);
+	for (i = 0; i <= 7; i++)
+		WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT8_PAGE_TABLE_BASE_ADDR + i,
+		       pd_gpu_addr >> 12);
+
+	/* Switch VC1_CNTL to DEPTH=1 + BLOCK_SIZE=2 (Sony's exact config). */
+	tmp = RREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT1_CNTL);
+	tmp = REG_SET_FIELD(tmp, VM_CONTEXT1_CNTL, PAGE_TABLE_DEPTH, 1);
+	tmp = REG_SET_FIELD(tmp, VM_CONTEXT1_CNTL, PAGE_TABLE_BLOCK_SIZE,
+			    PS4_UVD_CNTL_BLOCK_SIZE);
+	WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT1_CNTL, tmp);
+
+	/* Invalidate VC1..VC15 TLB entries. */
+	WREG32(mmVM_INVALIDATE_REQUEST, 0xfffe);
+	RREG32(mmVM_INVALIDATE_REQUEST);
+
+	DRM_INFO("ps4 uvd: B1 per-vmid PD ready — pd_gpu=0x%llx pt_gpu=0x%llx "
+		 "PD[0x%llx]=PDE, PT[0..%d]=PTEs, VC1..15 PT_BASE=0x%llx, "
+		 "CNTL DEPTH=1 BLOCK_SIZE=%d\n",
+		 pd_gpu_addr, pt_gpu_addr,
+		 (unsigned long long)PS4_UVD_PD_INDEX, mirror_pages - 1,
+		 pd_gpu_addr >> 12, PS4_UVD_CNTL_BLOCK_SIZE);
+
+	uvd_vmid_pd_done = true;
+	return 0;
+}
+
 static int uvd_v4_2_start_liverpool(struct amdgpu_device *adev)
 {
 	struct amdgpu_ring *ring = &adev->uvd.inst->ring;
@@ -593,6 +755,20 @@
 	}
 
 	/*
+	 * v76e-B1: build Sony-style per-vmid PD and repoint VC1..VC15 PT_BASE
+	 * at it (replaces the flat-walk override from β-2-A). Must come AFTER
+	 * fw_mirror_setup since the PT entries reference the mirror BO's
+	 * per-page DMA addresses.
+	 */
+	r = uvd_v4_2_setup_vmid_pd_liverpool(adev);
+	if (r) {
+		DRM_ERROR("ps4 uvd: B1 per-vmid PD setup failed (%d) — "
+			  "VCPU walk will fault\n", r);
+		/* continue anyway; the old flat-GART path still exists if
+		 * the gmc_v7_0 patches haven't been reverted */
+	}
+
+	/*
 	 * v74 diagnostics: hardware test of v73 showed the LMI base writes
 	 * have measurable effect (VM-fault page moved 0x300800 -> 0x300000,
 	 * vmid moved 14 -> 4 = mainline UVD vmid) but the VCPU still
